<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="346" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[130,645,265,358]" box="[130,333,265,290]" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">
<emphasis box="[130,333,265,290]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Taxonomic Notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[130,645,265,358]" lastBlockId="21.[683,1199,163,358]" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">
The recent specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[531,641,298,324]" name="Thailand" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, with a forearm length of 60.0 mm (
<tableCitation box="[546,637,331,358]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="23.[130,143,164,185]" captionText="TABLE 4. Four external measurements (in mm) and body mass (in g) of 10 specimens of seven bat species" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Table 4</tableCitation>
) and a condylo-canine length of 
<quantity box="[1087,1198,164,190]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.91" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" unit="mm" value="19.1">19.1 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[691,787,197,224]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="24.[124,151,1717,1730]" captionTargetBox="[261,551,167,1727]" captionTargetId="graphics@24.[295,557,160,1733]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="TABLE 5. Eleven cranial and dental measurements (in mm) of 11 specimens of eight bat species recently collected in Thailand, including the greatest length of skull (GTL), condylo-basal length (CBL), condylo-canine length (CCL), zygomatic breadth (ZB), breadth of braincase (BB), postorbital constriction (PC), maxillary toothrow length (C–M 3), palatal breadth (M 3 – M 3), anterior palatal breadth (C 1 – C 1), mandibular toothrow length (C–M), mandibular length (M). For Murina suilla, 3 the range, mean and standard deviation are given" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Table 5</tableCitation>
), agrees in size and morphology with the 
<typeStatus box="[808,912,231,257]" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[973,1123,231,257]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermani">
<emphasis box="[973,1123,231,257]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">M. hermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Sumatra (
<quantity box="[799,885,264,291]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" unit="mm" value="61.0">61 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[946,1056,264,291]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" unit="mm" value="19.5">19.5 mm</quantity>
, respective- ly). It is significantly larger than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Myotis formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(FA: 
<quantity box="[871,1051,331,358]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.68" metricValueMax="4.91" metricValueMin="4.45" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" unit="mm" value="46.8" valueMax="49.1" valueMin="44.5">44.5–49.1 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis box="[1069,1084,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">n</emphasis>
= 5 and
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944597" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3944597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944597/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" startId="21.[130,143,1679,1700]" targetBox="[128,1202,410,1669]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[130,1199,1679,1729]" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">
FIG. 2. A general view of part of Hala Forest and six bat species new to the fauna of Thailand: A — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robinson and Kloss" authorityYear="1911" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Hipposideros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ridleyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Hipposideros ridleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, B — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[253,400,1707,1729]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermani">
<emphasis box="[253,400,1707,1729]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Myotis hermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, C — 
<emphasis box="[462,596,1707,1729]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[462,592,1707,1729]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suilla">Murina suilla</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
D — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hill" authorityYear="1964" box="[653,785,1708,1729]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aenea">
<emphasis box="[653,785,1708,1729]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">Murina aenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, E — 
<emphasis box="[845,1038,1707,1728]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="345">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Waterhouse" baseAuthorityYear="1845" box="[845,1034,1707,1728]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Kerivoula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pellucida">Kerivoula pellucida</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
F — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1842" box="[1091,1143,1708,1729]" class="Mammalia" family="Molossidae" genus="Mops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="345" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Mops</taxonomicName>
mops
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,646,163,1383]" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">
CCL: 
<quantity box="[205,381,163,190]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6450000000000002" metricValueMax="1.6600000000000001" metricValueMin="1.6300000000000001" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" unit="mm" value="16.45" valueMax="16.6" valueMin="16.3">16.3–16.6 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis box="[394,409,164,189]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">n</emphasis>
= 4; measurements listed in 
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." box="[229,527,198,224]" journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref20396" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. Bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="Bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">Bates and Harrison, 1997</bibRefCitation>
), which is the only other species of Asian 
<taxonomicName box="[509,589,233,258]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[509,589,233,258]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cur- rently included in the subgenus 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Chryso- pteron</emphasis>
(sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="CORBET, G. B. &amp; J. E. HILL" bookContentInfo="488 pp." box="[302,571,300,326]" journalOrPublisher="Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref21586" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan Region. Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford, 488 pp." title="The mammals of the Indomalayan Region" type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill, 1992</bibRefCitation>
). Size apart, it shares most of the external charac- ters exhibited by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" box="[344,495,368,394]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[344,495,368,394]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It has con- spicuously orange (of various hues) and black parti-coloured wings and interfemoral membrane (
<figureCitation box="[273,364,470,497]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[130,143,1679,1700]" captionTargetBox="[128,1202,410,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[555,875,877,1362]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 2. A general view of part of Hala Forest and six bat species new to the fauna of Thailand: A — Hipposideros ridleyi, B — Myotis hermani, C — Murina suilla, D — Murina aenea, E — Kerivoula pellucida, F — Mops mops" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944597/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
). The ears are dark or- ange with black edges and have a concavity on the posterior border. The feet are not greatly enlarged. The hair roots are buff coloured and the tips orange, the latter frost- ed with black on both the dorsal and ventral aspects. Black frosting is not present in specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" box="[305,458,709,735]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[305,458,709,735]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seen from the Indian Subcontinent (
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref20396" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. Bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="Bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">Bates and Harrison, 1997</bibRefCitation>
) but the colouration is closely similar to that of an individual identified as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. wa- tasei</emphasis>
(= 
<taxonomicName authority="sensu Corbet and Hill, 1992" authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[227,374,845,871]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="CORBET, G. B. &amp; J. E. HILL" bookContentInfo="488 pp." journalOrPublisher="Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref21586" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan Region. Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford, 488 pp." title="The mammals of the Indomalayan Region" type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill, 1992</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="SIMMONS, N. B." bookContentInfo="2142 pp." box="[213,411,879,906]" journalOrPublisher="Johns Hopkins Univer- sity Press, Baltimore" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref25292" refString="SIMMONS, N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. Pp. 312 - 521, in Mammal species of the World: a taxonomic and geographical reference, 3 rd edition (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds.). Johns Hopkins Univer- sity Press, Baltimore, 2142 pp." title="Order Chiroptera. Pp. 312 - 521, in Mammal species of the World: a taxonomic and geographical reference, 3 rd edition (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds.)" type="book" year="2005">Simmons, 2005</bibRefCitation>
), a photograph of which is included in 
<bibRefCitation author="LIN, L. - K. &amp; L. - L. LEE &amp; H. - C. CHENG" bookContentInfo="177 pp." box="[384,587,913,940]" journalOrPublisher="National Museum of Natural Science, Taipei" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref23974" refString="LIN, L. - K., L. - L. LEE, and H. - C. CHENG. 2004. Bats of Taiwan. National Museum of Natural Science, Taipei, 177 pp." title="Bats of Taiwan" type="book" year="2004">
Lin 
<emphasis box="[434,488,913,939]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">et al</emphasis>
. (2004)
</bibRefCitation>
. The skull and dentition are comparable to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" box="[167,319,982,1008]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[167,319,982,1008]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(for details see 
<bibRefCitation author="BATES, P. J. J. &amp; D. L. HARRISON" bookContentInfo="258 pp." journalOrPublisher="Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref20396" refString="BATES, P. J. J., and D. L. HARRISON. 1997. Bats of the Indian Subcontinent. Harrison Zoological Museum, Sevenoaks, 258 pp." title="Bats of the Indian Subcontinent" type="book" year="1997">Bates and Harrison, 1997</bibRefCitation>
) in all aspects except for their considerably larger size.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,646,163,1383]" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">
<bibRefCitation author="FINDLEY, J. S." box="[168,360,1084,1110]" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Zoology" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" pagination="31 - 52" part="21" refId="ref21994" refString="FINDLEY, J. S. 1972. Phenetic relationships among bats of the genus Myotis. Systematic Zoology, 21: 31 - 52." title="Phenetic relationships among bats of the genus Myotis" type="journal article" year="1972">Findley (1972)</bibRefCitation>
included 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[501,602,1084,1110]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermani">
<emphasis box="[501,602,1084,1110]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">hermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" box="[309,460,1118,1144]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[309,460,1118,1144]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a view subse- quently followed by 
<bibRefCitation author="KOOPMAN, K. F." bookContentInfo="1206 pp." box="[367,569,1152,1179]" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington D. C" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref23792" refString="KOOPMAN, K. F. 1993. Order Chiroptera. Pp. 137 - 241, in Mammal species of the World: a taxonomic and geographic reference (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds.). Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington D. C., 1206 pp." title="Order Chiroptera. Pp. 137 - 241, in Mammal species of the World: a taxonomic and geographic reference (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds.)" type="book" year="1993">Koopman (1993)</bibRefCitation>
. How- ever, 
<bibRefCitation author="CORBET, G. B. &amp; J. E. HILL" bookContentInfo="488 pp." box="[194,463,1186,1212]" journalOrPublisher="Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" refId="ref21586" refString="CORBET, G. B., and J. E. HILL. 1992. The mammals of the Indomalayan Region. Natural History Museum Publications, Oxford University Press, Ox- ford, 488 pp." title="The mammals of the Indomalayan Region" type="book" year="1992">Corbet and Hill (1992)</bibRefCitation>
argued that the size of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[215,353,1220,1246]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermani">
<emphasis box="[215,353,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. hermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supports its specific dis- tinction, a view supported by the discovery of this recent specimen in 
<collectingCountry box="[486,594,1288,1314]" name="Thailand" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. As such, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[199,337,1322,1348]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hermani">
<emphasis box="[199,337,1322,1348]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. hermani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sensu Corbet and Hill" authorityYear="1992" box="[395,543,1323,1349]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="formosus">
<emphasis box="[395,543,1323,1349]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">M. formosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are here considered to be two distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="346" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,646,1431,1731]" box="[130,536,1431,1457]" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">
<emphasis box="[130,536,1431,1457]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Distribution and Ecological Notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,646,1431,1731]" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">
This is the first record from 
<collectingCountry box="[492,596,1465,1491]" name="Thailand" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and appears to be the first confirmed record of this bat since it was described from a single adult female collected from north-west Sumatra (
<bibRefCitation author="THOMAS, O." box="[244,418,1601,1628]" journalOrPublisher="Annals and Magazine of Natural History" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" pagination="250 - 255" part="11" refId="ref25690" refString="THOMAS, O. 1923. On some small mammals, chiefly bats, from the East Indian Archipelago. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 11: 250 - 255." title="On some small mammals, chiefly bats, from the East Indian Archipelago" type="journal article" year="1923">Thomas, 1923</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[130,646,1431,1731]" lastBlockId="22.[683,1199,163,561]" pageId="22" pageNumber="346">
The recent specimen, a mature fema- le, was captured in a mist net set over a seasonal small stream (
<quantity box="[465,520,1704,1731]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" unit="m" value="5.0">5 m</quantity>
wide) in Khuan Kaowang Forest Park. The capture site was on the edge of secondary tropical lowland rain forest (ca. 350 ha at 100–200 m a.s.l.), which is characterized by many large standing trees and a dense shrub layer. It appeared that the bat, which was caught at 20:00 hours at a height of 
<quantity box="[1060,1134,366,393]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" unit="m" value="1.5">1.5 m</quantity>
, was travelling from the forest to an area of rubber plantations and dry scrub woodland. Its body was covered with a 
<quantity box="[985,1053,468,494]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="346" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
layer of fat. Possibly this was an energy reserve for the breeding period.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
